=========================================================
PROCESS vs THREAD (C++ INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition
----------

Process:
A process is an independent program in execution with its own memory space and resources.

Thread:
A thread is the smallest unit of execution within a process. Multiple threads of the same process share the process resources.

---------------------------------------------------------

Key Differences

| Process | Thread |
|---------|---------|
| Independent program | Smallest execution unit inside a process |
| Has its own memory | Shares process memory |
| Heavyweight | Lightweight |
| Creation is slower | Creation is faster |
| Context switch is expensive | Context switch is cheaper |
| Communication uses IPC | Communication through shared memory |
| Failure usually doesn't affect other processes | One thread can affect the entire process |

---------------------------------------------------------

Memory

Each Process Has:
- Separate Code
- Separate Heap
- Separate Stack
- Separate Global Variables

Threads of Same Process Share:
- Code
- Heap
- Global Variables

Each Thread Has Its Own:
- Stack
- Registers
- Program Counter

---------------------------------------------------------

Real-world Example

Google Chrome

Each browser tab → Separate Process

Inside one tab:
- UI Thread
- Network Thread
- JavaScript Thread
- Rendering Thread

---------------------------------------------------------

Advantages of Threads

✓ Faster execution
✓ Better CPU utilization
✓ Lower memory usage
✓ Faster communication (shared memory)
✓ Improved responsiveness

---------------------------------------------------------

Disadvantages of Threads

✓ Race conditions
✓ Deadlocks
✓ Synchronization complexity
✓ One thread crash may terminate the process

---------------------------------------------------------

When to Use Process?

- High isolation required
- Better fault tolerance
- Security
- Independent applications

Examples:
- Chrome tabs
- VS Code
- Microsoft Word

---------------------------------------------------------

When to Use Threads?

- Tasks share data
- Better performance
- Parallel execution

Examples:
- Web server handling requests
- File download + UI
- Game engine
- Image processing

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview Answer (30 Seconds)

"A process is an independent program with its own memory space, whereas a 
thread is a lightweight execution unit inside a process. Threads share code, 
heap, and global data but have their own stack and registers. Threads are faster to create 
and communicate efficiently through shared memory, while processes provide better isolation and fault tolerance."

---------------------------------------------------------

Memory Trick

Process
→ Separate Memory
→ Heavyweight
→ IPC Communication

Thread
→ Shared Memory
→ Lightweight
→ Fast Communication
